description:
Choosing the right data type matters.
For numbers, the two most commonly used are:
  int - integers, stores whole numbers only no decimals.
    int age = 20;
    int score = 100;
    int temperature = -5;

  double - stores numbers with decimals.
    double price = 19.99;
    double height = 5.9;
    double pi = 3.14159;

Here's an example of comparison.
Try it:
  int a = 5;
  int b = 2;

  cout << a / b;   

The output will be 2.
Now change them to double:
  double a = 5;
  double b = 2;

  cout << a / b;
The output will be 2.5
Notice the difference of the output.

Same numbers.
Different data types.
Different result.

Why?
Because int removes the decimal part.

Data types define what kind of data a variable can store and how much memory it uses. Choosing the correct data type is important for accuracy and performance. Common data types in C++ include int for integers, double for decimal values, bool for true or false values, and string for text.

So far, you’ve learned int and double.
Now let’s complete the foundation with:
  const - a constant is a variable whose value cannot be changed after it is created. You use the keyword const.
    const double PI = 3.14159;
    const int DAYS_IN_WEEK = 7;
  char - stores a single character.
    char grade = 'A';
    char letter = 'Z';
  string - tores text.
    string name = "John";
    string message = "Hello World";
  bool - tores only two values: true or false.
    bool isLoggedIn = true;
    bool isFinished = false;

Congratulations! You've already learned Basic Data Types.

Let's dive right away to a Practice Challenge.
Shall we. Gyahahaha!

