description:
Now your program can compare values.
But what if you want to check multiple conditions at the same time?
That’s where Logical Operators come in.
They help combine comparison results.

Logical operators work with true and false values.
Here are the three main ones:
  &&  -   AND	   
  Both conditions must be true.
    int age = 20;
    cout << (age > 18 && age < 30);

  Output: 1
  Because 20 is greater than 18 AND less than 30.
  If one condition is false → result is false (0).

  ||  -   OR 
  At least one condition must be true.
    int num = 5;
    cout << (num < 3 || num > 2);

  Output: 1
  Even though num < 3 is false,
  num > 2 is true — so the result is true.


  ! -   NOT
  Reverses the result.
    int x = 10;
    cout << !(x > 5);

  Output: 0
  x > 5 is true.
  !true becomes false.

Example with user input:
  int score;
  cout << "Enter your score: ";
  cin >> score;

  cout << (score >= 50 && score <= 100);

This checks if the score is between 50 and 100.

