description:
You can store values.
You can update values.
You can compare and combine conditions.

Now it’s time to make your program choose what to do.

Welcome to the if statement.
An if statement lets your program run some code only if a condition is true.
  if (condition) {
      // code runs only if condition is true
  }

Example: Check a Number
  int num;
  cout << "Enter a number: ";
  cin >> num;

  if (num > 0) {
      cout << "This is a positive number." << endl;
  }

If the user enters 5 → prints: This is a positive number.
If the user enters -3 → prints nothing.
What if you want to do something when the condition is false?
  if (num > 0) {
    cout << "Positive" << endl;
  } else {
      cout << "Not positive" << endl;
  }

num = 5 - Positive
num = -3 - Not positive

Tips
Conditions usually use comparison (==, >, <) or logical operators (&&, ||, !).
You can also nest if statements for multiple decisions.
  if (num > 0) {
    cout << "Positive" << endl;
  } else if (num < 0) {
      cout << "Negative" << endl;
  } else {
      cout << "Zero" << endl;
  }

