description:
Arrow functions are a shorter way to write functions in JavaScript.

They use the => symbol.

Instead of writing:

function greet(name) {
  return "Hello " + name;
}

We can write:

const greet = (name) => {
  return "Hello " + name;
};

If the function has only one line that returns a value,
we can simplify it even more:

const greet = (name) => "Hello " + name;

Arrow functions make code cleaner and more modern.

They are commonly used in JavaScript today.

Objects can store data.

But they can also store functions.

When a function is stored inside an object,
it is called a method.

A method is simply a function that belongs to an object.

Example:

let person = {
  name: "Sakura",
  greet: function() {
    console.log("Hello!");
  }
};

Here:

name is a property

greet is a method

To call a method, we use dot notation followed by parentheses.

person.greet();

Output:

Hello!

Methods allow objects to perform actions.

Objects can now store both data and behavior.
